An amazing race and a unique way to explore LA. August and Emilie were great racing buddies, and while it may not have been my best race, it was still the most fun I've had on a run in a long time (at least the first 20 miles). Big thanks to Axel, Gaurav, and Simon for being an excellent support crew, and also thanks to all the volunteers and people cheering around the course!

Official Time - 3:12:19 // Race Recap: Started out a bit fast (partly due to the downhill and to escape the mob of runners, also partially due to excitement and bad pacing), but after the first few miles I settled into a consistent rhythm. I think I may have gone a bit too hard on the steep downhills though because my quads started to ache by the HM mark. This was bearable, but the real issue occurred in the middle of mile 21 where I started to get sudden cramp spasms in my right calf, and a couple of miles later my left calf as well. It eventually got to the point where I was forced to stop and relieve the strains every few minutes, so the last 5 miles of this race were incredibly painful. Had the same thing on my last marathon but it only started on the last mile, so I'm not sure exactly what causes it (maybe a combination of going out too fast and not intaking enough electrolytes?). By mile 24 my goal was just to finish with as few stops as possible, and I ended up practically hopping across the finish line. But other than the cramps, I'm really happy with how the race went. It was certainly a learning experience. BQ is coming next year :)

Official Time: 2:59:56!! 

Literally came down to the final stretch, very glad I ran through the finish; I cannot believe I managed to pull this off. Just like last time, a super fun course with lots of support from the race crew and spectators! Also, a huge congrats to Axel for running an even faster sub 3 on his first marathon (😳), and a big thanks to him for being an amazing training partner!

Race Recap: I told myself I wasn’t gonna go out too fast, and I didn’t feel like I was going out too fast, but in hindsight my first two miles were way too fast. Still, after the first few miles I found a nice rhythm and was able to stay on pace (taking into consideration the elevation change). The head wind was absolutely insane so I tried to stick with the 3:00 pacer group, but for some reason they were going well below 3 flat pace (they hit the HM mark at like 1:27), so I decided it was just better to stick with what felt comfortable and battle the wind on my own. 

The main difference in strategy I implemented this race was taking the downhills easy, and I think this ended up saving me minutes in the long run (last LA marathon the force on my quads from the pounding of the downhill made them incredibly sore early on in the race which was a big nono).

Once again, my limiting factor was the terrible calf cramps. I felt the first twinge right at the 20 mile mark, so I instantly slowed down to try and delay the inevitable spasms. They got really bad at mile 23, but this time whenever they came on I just stopped to stretch and was able to get back to ~MP pace (so I was pretty much running 6:50s + 20sec stops for each of the last miles), which worked much better than just trying to push through the cramps like I did last time.

The final 100m stretch was excruciating because I practically had to gallop (somehow at sub 5 pace) to the finish line through the cramps to make it just under 3 hours (definitely worth it).

I think the main thing I need to improve on is figuring out how to drink liquid from the aid station cups while in motion, because if i’m going at anything faster than a walk I end up losing at least 75% of the contents. 

But overall, I’m incredibly happy with the outcome. Really did not want to have to wait another 4 months for a sub 3 :)

Official time - 2:58:07 // Race recap: The flat start made it much easier to settle into a comfortable race pace and effort, but boy were the hills brutal compared to LA (1700ft of gain officially, which I didn’t realize until like a day before the race). Writing goal paces on my arms was honestly a godsend because it let me stay relaxed on the climbs where I was going way slower than MP. The bridge was INSANELY windy and there wasn’t really a pack to draft with, so I just took those miles easy and stuck with runners as they passed me. Still, the fog was lovely and overall conditions were excellent. Hydration was messy the first half but it got better as the race went on. Around miles 16 and 17 my quads were so dead from the steep ups and downs that I was afraid they would just give out on me, but luckily the last 10k was largely flat and gradual downhill so I recovered and was able to pick up the pace. I felt twinges of calf cramps starting at mile 22 so I stayed relaxed until the last 3 miles and when I realized they weren’t gonna get me this time I just sent it. 2:58 was already a PR, and according to a race equivalency calculator I found online it converts to around a 2:55 something at LA, so I definitely feel like I’ve improved since march despite the wonky training plan due to getting covid on the first week :/. This was also significantly less painful than the previous marathons (probably due to better pacing), and easily one of my favorite runs of all time!

Official Time: 2:56:59 // My main goal for this race was to not get calf cramps. But there's something about mile 20 on this course that gets me every time, and I could tell my right calf was going to seize, so I had to dial it back.  A couple miles later it seemed pretty much back to normal so I picked up the pace and finished strong, so overall I would say that goal was achieved. I went pretty heavy on the electrolytes after it started to feel iffy so maybe that helped? 

Secondary goals were to have decent pacing and PR while not absolutely destroying my legs. My HR was like 8bpm higher than what it was for my past couple marathons so I was terrified of bonking,  but I felt good so I just ignored it and went by feel (which luckily ended up working out).  Pacing could've been a little better (specifically miles 3-4 were faster than they should've been), but overall it was waaay better than my previous attempts at the course.  Felt much stronger on the downhills (probably due focusing more on strength work this training block),  and hydration/fueling was spot on. ~1min PR (and 3min CR), and the legs feel markedly better than they felt post LAM1 and 2.  Very high hopes for next month.

2:54:30 (2.5min PR from LA last month)! This experience was absolutely incredible, and the race was one of a kind. I think I’m gonna take a break from marathons for a while, but I’ll definitely be back for this race.

Race recap: I don’t even know where to start. Spent the weekend visiting my old hometown so that was pretty nostalgic, and then staying right across the street from the start was quite a treat. Saw all the elites warming up and even got a smile from my running idol mr kipchoge (try and spot him in this high quality clip). I was absolutely not mentally prepared for the sheer amount of runners there were at the start. Took about 4 miles for the pack to thin out enough for me to really go at my own pace, but overall it wasn’t too much of an issue (if anything it helped keep my start conservative). The rain also got pretty heavy right before the start so I was almost soaked before the race had even begun. Still weather conditions were not terrible; having so many people to draft behind minimized the headwind and the downpour only happened through the last few miles. I’m glad I got quite a few rainy runs in during this training block, it definitely made me feel more prepared for the conditions. Watch died right around mile 18, but that was to be expected. Didn’t really know what pace I was going from that point onwards but the nearby runners helped me run consistently at least. Overall pacing ended up being much better than expected, with about a 1min negative split. No calf cramps thank god, but glutes and quads were pretty demolished. Glad I was able to finish strong. The energy of the crowds was incredible, especially running by Wellesley and Northeastern. Such a fun race, can’t wait to do it again.
